---
title: Harvest Flatbread with Butternut Squash, Apples,  and Sage
description: Sage is a Mediterranean herb with narrow, gray-green leaves and a slightly bitter taste reminiscent of mint. Although commonly used in poultry dishes, our chefs love it when paired with creamy butternut squash, crunchy apples, and caramelized onions.
image: https://img.hellofresh.com/f_auto,fl_lossy,h_640,q_auto,w_1200/hellofresh_s3/image/butternut-squash-and-caramelized-0232ac2c.jpg
pdf: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipecards/card/butternut-squash-and-caramelized-8f3a3429.pdf
time required: 30 minutes
author: HelloFresh
servings: 2
cuisine: North America
nutrition:
  calories: 636 kcal
  fat: 28 g
  saturated fat: 11 g
  carbohydrates: 82 g
  sugar: 21 g
  protein: 23 g
  fiber: 10 g
  sodium: 733 mg
source: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipes/harvest-flatbread-57e2f852bfba3d47b802ccb2
course: main course
---

Wash and dry all produce. Preheat oven to 425°. Peel, halve, and thinly slice @Red Onion{1}. Finely chop @Sage{1/4%ounce}(finely chopped) leaves.

Toss @Butternut Squash{8%ounce} on a #baking sheet{} with a drizzle of @Olive Oil{1%tablespoon}, the @Chili Powder{1%teaspoon}, and a pinch of @Salt{} and @Pepper{}. Bake ~{10-12%minutes}. Toss, then continue to roast until golden brown, another ~{10-12%minutes}.

Heat a drizzle of @Olive Oil{} in a large pan over medium heat. Add onion and half the sage. Toss until softened, ~{4-5%minutes}. Add ½ cup water and cook until jammy, another ~{10-15%minutes}.

Place @Flatbreads{2} on a lightly oiled baking sheet, and bake until beginning to brown on edges, ~{5-7%minutes}.

Core and thinly slice @Granny Smith Apple{1}(core removed and thinly sliced). Top flatbreads with @Cheddar Cheese{1%cup}, roasted butternut squash, caramelized onions, and apple slices.

Sprinkle with remaining sage, then drizzle with @Honey{1%tablespoon}. Bake until cheese has melted, ~{5-7%minutes}. Cut into slices and enjoy!

> Sage is a Mediterranean herb with narrow, gray-green leaves and a slightly bitter taste reminiscent of mint. Although commonly used in poultry dishes, our chefs love it when paired with creamy butternut squash, crunchy apples, and caramelized onions.